      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Non-Resident Tax Timing When Selling a Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        If you are a foreign tax resident selling a Brisbane property, the timing of your residency, clearance certificate, settlement date, and the Australian financial year end can each move your tax position materially. Here is how to think about the calendar.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most articles about non-resident vendors selling Australian property focus on the rules: the foreign resident capital gains withholding regime, the loss of the main residence exemption for foreign tax residents, the higher marginal rates that apply to non-resident taxable income. Those rules matter, but the rules are largely fixed; what is genuinely negotiable for a non-resident vendor selling a Brisbane home is the timing. When you list, when you sign, when you settle, and when (or whether) your Australian tax residency status changes can each move your final tax position by tens of thousands of dollars on a typical inner-east sale. This article walks through the calendar variables that matter, in the order they tend to come up.</p>

      <p>Before going further, the standard caveat: tax outcomes depend on individual circumstances and on rules that change over time. Nothing here is tax advice. The point of the article is to help you ask the right questions of a registered tax agent or accountant who is familiar with cross-border property matters, so that you do not arrive at settlement having overlooked a timing lever you could have used.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why timing matters more for non-residents than for residents</h2>
      <p>For an Australian tax resident selling a primary place of residence, the headline tax question is usually whether the main residence exemption applies and to what extent. For a foreign tax resident selling the same property, the question set is wider: the main residence exemption is generally not available at all (with limited transitional carve-outs), the foreign resident capital gains withholding regime applies at settlement, the gain is assessed against non-resident marginal rates without the tax-free threshold, and the 50 per cent capital gains discount available to individual residents is not available in the same form. Each of these levers is sensitive to the date on which the contract is signed, the date settlement occurs, and the tax residency status of the vendor on those dates. Small differences in calendar position produce large differences in the cheque that ultimately leaves the seller's account.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The contract date is the CGT event date</h2>
      <p>For most property sales, the capital gains tax event is taken to occur on the date of the contract, not the settlement date. This is a foundational point that surprises a number of non-resident vendors, who assume the financial position only crystallises when the money moves at settlement. From a CGT perspective, the gain is locked in when both parties sign. The financial year in which that contract date falls determines the financial year in which the gain is assessable. A contract signed on 28 June and settling on 14 August will, for CGT purposes, sit in the earlier financial year, even though no money changed hands until the later one. A contract signed on 2 July and settling on 14 August will sit in the later financial year. The difference is six days on the contract date and twelve months on the tax year, and that distinction can move when the tax is payable, which year's other income it is offset against, and which residency status applies for the assessment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Residency status at the CGT event date</h2>
      <p>Australian tax residency is assessed on the facts: where you live, where your home is, where your family is, where your work is, where your assets sit, and how you spend your time across the year. Residency is not a status you choose by ticking a box; it follows from the actual circumstances. For non-resident vendors, the practical question is which side of the residency line you sit on at the contract date. A vendor who returns to Australia and re-establishes residency before signing contracts may have a meaningfully different tax outcome to a vendor who signs while still overseas. Equally, a vendor who is in the process of moving overseas and signs the contract before the move may have a different outcome to one who signs after. The contract date is the point at which residency is locked in for the purposes of that CGT event.</p>

      <p>This does not mean you can manufacture residency to suit a tax outcome. The Australian Taxation Office looks at the substance of your living arrangements, not the date you arrived in the country. But it does mean that if you are genuinely transitioning between residency statuses for life or work reasons, the contract date relative to that transition is worth thinking about with your accountant before you list.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The foreign resident capital gains withholding regime</h2>
      <p>If you are a foreign tax resident selling Australian real property and the contract price exceeds the relevant threshold, the buyer is required by law to withhold a percentage of the contract price at settlement and remit it to the Australian Taxation Office. The withheld amount is not the final tax; it is a prepayment that is reconciled against your eventual assessment when you lodge the return for the year of the CGT event. The practical effect at settlement is that you receive less cash than the contract price suggests. If your actual tax liability is lower than the withheld amount, you receive the difference as a refund after lodgement; if it is higher, you pay the difference at lodgement. The withholding rate and threshold have changed over time and may change again, so confirm the current settings with your accountant before signing contracts.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the clearance certificate timing is critical</h2>
      <p>Australian tax residents selling Australian real property can apply to the Australian Taxation Office for a clearance certificate. If a valid clearance certificate is provided to the buyer at or before settlement, the buyer does not have to withhold under the foreign resident regime. Clearance certificates are typically valid for twelve months and can be applied for in advance of any contract. For vendors who are Australian tax residents but have international elements to their circumstances (foreign citizenship, recent overseas residency, complex domicile, beneficial ownership through a foreign-resident structure), applying for the clearance certificate early is one of the most useful timing decisions in the campaign. The certificate often issues quickly but can take several weeks where the ATO needs more information. A vendor who waits until contracts are signed to apply may find themselves at settlement without the certificate in hand, which forces the buyer to withhold even though the vendor would have qualified for an exemption.</p>

      <p>If you are clearly a foreign tax resident, the clearance certificate is not available to you. In that case, the timing question shifts to managing the withholding around your overall tax position rather than avoiding it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Settlement date and cash flow timing</h2>
      <p>Settlement date determines when the funds (less withholding, less commission, less other settlement costs) actually reach the vendor's bank account. Most non-resident vendors are repatriating those funds offshore, often through foreign exchange transactions that themselves take time and incur cost. A settlement date that aligns with a favourable foreign exchange position, with the vendor's offshore tax planning calendar, or with the timing of an offshore replacement purchase can be substantially more useful than a settlement date that does not. In a private treaty negotiation, settlement date is generally negotiable within reason: a thirty, sixty, or ninety day settlement is the typical range, with longer settlements available where both parties agree. For non-resident vendors, the settlement date is rarely the primary commercial term, but it should not be left to default. It is worth raising explicitly with the agent and the conveyancer as part of the contract drafting process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Six-year absence rule and pre-foreign-resident periods</h2>
      <p>Vendors who occupied the property as their main residence before becoming foreign residents may have access to partial main residence exemption depending on the timing of their absence and the use of the property during that absence. The rules around the six-year absence concession have been tightened for foreign residents in recent years, with grandfathering provisions for properties held before specific cut-off dates. The interaction between the date the property was acquired, the date the seller departed Australia, the date the seller's residency changed, the date the property was first rented (if at all), and the date the contract is signed produces a multi-variable problem that needs to be modelled with an accountant. For some vendors, signing contracts shortly before a residency change has a different tax outcome to signing shortly after. For others, the timing makes no material difference. The point is that you cannot tell which case applies to you without working the calculation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Australian financial year end (30 June) considerations</h2>
      <p>The Australian financial year ends on 30 June. CGT events that occur on or before 30 June are assessable in that financial year; CGT events that occur from 1 July onwards are assessable in the next. For non-resident vendors with control over the contract date, this calendar break point is occasionally meaningful. It can matter where the vendor expects significantly different non-resident taxable income across the two years (for example, a year of capital losses available to offset a gain, versus a year without). It can also matter where there is anticipated legislative change with effect from a specific date, although relying on legislative timing is rarely a sound primary strategy. For most non-resident vendors, the financial year position is a secondary consideration that is worth checking with the accountant rather than the leading driver of the listing date.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the foreign country's tax year matters too</h2>
      <p>Many non-resident vendors are tax residents of a country with its own financial year and its own rules around how the Australian gain interacts with their foreign tax position. The United States, the United Kingdom, Canada, New Zealand, Singapore, Hong Kong, the United Arab Emirates, and several European jurisdictions each treat Australian-sourced capital gains differently, with double tax agreements and foreign tax credit mechanisms that depend on the timing of the assessment in both countries. A contract signed in late June crystallises the Australian CGT event in one Australian financial year and is reported on the foreign side in whichever foreign tax year the foreign rules treat the gain as arising. Misalignment between the two calendars can produce timing mismatches that delay foreign tax credits or push the gain into a foreign tax year with different rates. Non-resident vendors who are paying tax in two jurisdictions should be running the calendar with an accountant who understands both sides, not just the Australian side.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical sequence for a non-resident vendor</h2>
      <p>If you are selling a Brisbane property as a foreign tax resident or someone with cross-border elements, a practical sequence runs roughly as follows. Engage an Australian accountant familiar with non-resident CGT before listing. Confirm whether you are eligible for a clearance certificate; if so, lodge the application early. Run the gain calculation with your accountant to understand the order of magnitude of withholding and final liability. Discuss the contract date and settlement date implications relative to the Australian financial year and your foreign tax year. Brief your conveyancer on the residency position so the contract documentation aligns. Brief your selling agent so that the campaign timing, contract negotiation, and settlement date are managed with the tax position in mind, not just the price. Time spent on this sequencing in the weeks before listing tends to be more valuable than time spent on it after a contract is already signed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What an experienced local agent can and cannot help with</h2>
      <p>A selling agent is not a tax adviser and will not give you tax advice. What a good local agent can do is run the campaign in a way that respects the timing constraints your accountant has identified, negotiate contract dates and settlement dates with the buyer's representative in line with your preferred calendar, and coordinate with your conveyancer so that nothing is missed at settlement. For non-resident vendors selling Brisbane inner-east property, that coordination is the practical value the agent adds beyond the obvious work of marketing and price negotiation. The numbers that matter on the tax side will be set by your accountant, but the calendar that those numbers run against is set in the campaign.</p>

